  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Suspense is the reader\u0026rsquo;s experience of uncertain anticipation — the state of knowing that something important is about to happen without knowing what it will be or how it will turn out. It is tension directed toward the future: the reader wants to know what happens next badly enough to keep reading.\nAlfred Hitchcock distinguished suspense from surprise. Surprise is the bomb going off under the table without warning — a shock that lasts seconds. Suspense is showing the audience the bomb under the table and then letting the characters have their conversation — the audience knows something the characters don\u0026rsquo;t, and that knowledge creates unbearable anticipation. Surprise is a moment; suspense is a sustained state.\n",
